[normal]&#xa0;[bold]11. What should be the relationship betwee[bold]n the Parliamentary and Health S[bold]ervice Ombudsman and[bold]Answer[bold]: [bold]As a body [bold]of final appeal, when a department’s complaints procedure has not given satisfaction[bold] to the citizen[bold].
[normal]Answer[bold]: The Ombudsman should cease to be an officer of Parliament[bold], [bold]should [bold]become independent, [bold]and[bold] should[bold] be [bold]financed by the departments it covers.[bold]As a creature of Parliament
[normal], the
[normal] PHSO has not b
[normal]een properly held to account
[normal] by Parliament.
[normal] 
[normal]To the citizen
[normal], PHSO accountability 
[normal]seems to consist
[normal] of producing 
[normal]a glos
[normal]sy annual
[normal] report
[normal],
[normal] and an annual 
[normal]cant
[normal]er by the Ombudsman before 
[normal]the PASC. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A citizen 
[normal]with a complaint 
[normal]can 
[normal]be made to 
[normal]feel he is 
[normal]taking on the 
[normal]Establishment
[normal] 
[normal]fronted 
[normal]by the PHSO, 
[normal]which g
[normal]ives a privileged position not only 
[normal]to the 
[normal]Department 
[normal](vis-à-vis the citizen
[normal]) but 
[normal]to 
[normal]the MP who gets the f
[normal]inal letter from the Ombudsman (on first-name terms in my case) 
[normal]wi
[normal]th 
[normal]just 
[normal]a copy 
[normal]to the citizen
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The office of Ombudsman would surely be more conv
[normal]incing to the citizen 
[normal]if the
[normal] holder was not seen as 
[normal]part of the Establishment. The current Ombudsman was appointed a Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire 
[normal]‘for services to equal opportunities’ 
[normal]- after heading the Equal Opportunities Commission for eight years.  All other Ombudsmen with one exception have been ‘Sirs’.
[normal]  The PASC published a report criticising the giving of honours to people for doing their day job, 
[normal]yet it went 
[normal]along with 
[normal](presumably) 
[normal]appointing such a member of the Establishment as the current Ombudsman.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Ombudsman should 
[normal]be independent, financed by the departments
[normal] it covers. For every 
[normal]admissible complaint 
[normal]that reaches the Ombudsman, a department should 
[normal]also 
[normal]pay a fee. 
[normal]In this way, each 
[normal]select committ
[normal]ee 
[normal]can get involved
[normal] with its de
[normal]partment’s complaints procedures
[normal] and outcomes
[normal].
[normal]Answer[bold]: [bold]Continuation of [bold]the [bold]present[bold] relationship, but on a less chummy basis.[bold]Any 
[normal]kind of broader relationship between the PHSO and the PASC is difficult to envisage
[normal].  
[normal]It is 
[normal]surely 
[normal]the
[normal] PASC 
[normal]which 
[normal]has allowed the present sorry state of affairs to develop. 
[normal]T
[normal]he PASC works mainly in private, meeting only 
[normal]occasional
[normal]ly in public, 
[normal]to ‘take evidence’.  At the time of writing (mid-September 2013), the Committee has not met since publ
[normal]icly since 2 July 2013, and 
[normal]currently 
[normal]has 
[normal]no scheduled 
[normal]public 
[normal]meetings (although a hearing is 
[normal]mentioned 
[normal]for October
[normal] 2013
[normal]).  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The PASC secretariat may share the same address 
[normal]as the PHSO, but they can hardly 
[normal]take any initiative without the say-so of the
[normal]ir
[normal] MPs. 
