[normal]&#xa0;[bold]13. Should citizens have direct access to the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman for all complaints, as people already have in respect of complaints about the [bold]NHS?[bold]Answer: [bold]Direct[bold] access[bold] for all[bold], without having to go through an MP.[bold]As things stand, there is even a lack of precision as to whether one can go through 
[normal]any
[normal] MP, or only the constituency MP. In my case, as a complainant living outside the UK, PHSO wording implied I could only go though Mr Jenkin MP (as chairman of the PASC). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The arguments for retaining the ‘MP filter’ seem to rest on a rather idealised view of MPs’ relationships with their constituents. Most people do not know who their MP is (80 %?). People move residence between elections. Many will have never voted for their MP, given the UK electoral system, and may be disinclined to go to the ‘opposition’. Some may know another MP better, through circumstances. Then people get ‘disenfranchised’ for weeks when there are by-elections and general elections, and a new MP has to recruit staff and learn the ropes.  There must be nagging doubts about whether, or when, a certain MP will deal with a case, because of some highly-publicised activity which clearly impinges on their ‘day job’, or because the MP is an important Minister, or simply because of the many recesses when people are not sure if the MP is around. Others might wonder if the MP 
[normal]would indeed forward the case, because the complaint fortuitously goes against that MP’s known
[normal] political agenda, or sponsors
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What should [bold]be [bold]the relationship betwee[bold]n the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman and MPs [bold]and how can it work[bold]?[bold]Could the [bold]Parliamentary and Health S[bold]ervice Ombudsman do more to support MPs[bold]’[bold] handling of complaints[bold] on behalf of [bold]constituents?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Answer[bold]: [bold]This is [bold]more [bold]for[bold] the[bold] 650 MPs to answer[bold] (11 [bold]MPs [bold]are on the PASC).[bold]&#xa0;
